            <link>https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/say-quoi-4</link>
            <guid>https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/say-quoi-4</guid>
            <pubDate>Mon, 19 Feb 2024 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[Ottawa does traffic signage different than Qu√©bec.]]></description>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Remember that grotesque <a href="https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/say-quoi-2">traffic sign from Qu√©bec</a> that said ¬´ Attention √† nos enfants ¬ª and depicted a hurt child lying on the ground? Compare it to this one by the <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/city-of-ottawa" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">City of Ottawa</a>:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" src="https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/D4E22AQFuiyUAuZZywQ/feedshare-shrink_2048_1536/0/1708214563073?e=1711584000&amp;v=beta&amp;t=rNzEDCJ61baV4jlDrhV0D0wlLw0Zmey9EhsXdI_sMnE" alt="A bilingual traffic sign in Ottawa that reads, &quot;Slow down for us,&quot; and depicts silhouettes of children at play." class="img_ev3q"></p>
<ul>
<li>Same message ‚Üí "slow down"</li>
<li>Same concept ‚Üí text + picture of children</li>
<li>Different execution ‚Üí the children are alive (and having fun)</li>
</ul>
<p>Which one is more effective in making drivers slow down and preventing accidents, I wonder ... and if it's the panneau qu√©becois, does the end justify the means?</p>]]></content:encoded>
