            <link>https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/typo-question-mark</link>
            <guid>https://igorcasmarques.github.io/micro-blog/typo-question-mark</guid>
            <pubDate>Wed, 14 Feb 2024 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
            <description><![CDATA[Depends who you ask.]]></description>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Who is going to tell Gr... actually, hold on.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" src="https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/D4D22AQEjOLwpN_-wYg/feedshare-shrink_800/0/1707924425732?e=1710979200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=7aF5PI1-6VUZ1Qg8xhEy9cf9JZMjZ1-jD-iUWgnmmVQ" alt="A sign says that &quot;the premises is under 24-hour surveillance." class="img_ev3q"></p>
<p>"Premises" is a plural noun, so it should be "The premises are under ... surveillance." At least that's what my dictionaries tell me. So, there! Fix your sign! Right?</p>
<p>Actually, there seems to be a growing trend of using "premises" as a singular noun in North America. Like a fancy synonym for "building" or "property." Particularly in insurance-speak.</p>
<p>Check out this <a href="https://www.squareone.ca/resource-centres/insurance-glossary/premises" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">definition by Square One</a>, an insurance brokerage operating in several provinces.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" src="https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/D4D22AQFn1aRJh8eTqw/feedshare-shrink_800/0/1707924424011?e=1710979200&amp;v=beta&amp;t=3Jh1V2Vcs-qbCs2EK74cBKUJYu3KALVVVR36yA3FQYM" alt="Square One uses &quot;premises&quot; as a singular countable noun, i.e., &quot;a premises.&quot;" class="img_ev3q"></p>
<p>What was that about the mote and the beam...</p>]]></content:encoded>
